Equipment required: 25 cards numbered with odd numbers from 1 to 49, illustrating the story of Don Quixote and 25 cards numbered with even numbers from 2 to 50, each with a printed rhymed couplet
card teetotum number 1 to 6 
printed rules sheet
wooden box divided into two compartments, with sliding lid


Rules:
DON QUIXOTE DIRECTIONS FOR PLAYING THE GAME

The eldest player is to read aloud the rules while others lay the cards consecutively, beinging with No. 1 to No. 50.
The players, in turn, spin the Teetotum and take the card corresponding in number and afterwards add the number of each spin to the number of their last card, taking the card numbered to correspond with the two added together; and if such number has already been taken, the spin does not count.
The card numbered 41,44,46 may be taken by the spinner getting those numbers, although they already be taken by another player; and if the card given up be that player's highest number, he counts from the highest still in his hand.
When No. 50 is taken it ends the game and the cards are to be counted as follows:  for every card with Rhyme count 1; for each picture card count 2; for the card 43 count 4; for No. 50 count 6.  The numbers countained in each player's had to be added up; the highest wins the game and seated in the chair of honour, demands forfeits of the others.
These rules may be modified at pleasure by the players
*The rhymes refer to the picture of the preceding number.
